'''Janette Bertrand''' (born March 25, 1925) is a [[Quebec]] journalist, actor, educator, and writer.<ref name=ce/>
She was born in [[Montreal]], grew up there, and studied journalism at the [[Université de Montréal]]. She began work at the ''Petit Journal'', working there for 16 years. She next moved to radio, becoming the host of the [[Ici Radio-Canada Télé|Radio-Canada]] program ''Déjeuner en musique'' in the early 1950s. Bertrand married the actor [[Jean Lajeunesse]]. The couple hosted the program ''Jean et Janette'', and then ''Mon mari et nous'' at radio station [[CKAC]]. Later, she began appearing on television for Radio-Canada, [[TVA (Canada)|Télé-Métropole]] and [[Télé-Québec|Radio-Québec]]. She developed the television series ''[[Grand-Papa (TV series)|Grand-Papa]]'',<ref name=ce/> ''[[L'Amour avec un Grand A]]'', and ''Parler pour parler''.<ref name=ordre/>
Bertrand received a [[Governor General's Awards#Governor General.27s Performing Arts Awards|Governor General's Performing Arts Awards]] in 2000.<ref name=ce>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/janette-bertrand/ |title=Janette Bertrand |encyclopedia=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}</ref> She also received several [[Gemini Award]]s, including one for Lifetime Achievement, the Order of Merit from the Canadian Association of Radio Broadcasters,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ggpaa.ca/award-recipients/bertrand-janette.aspx |title=Janette Bertrand |work=Governor General's Performing Arts Awards}}</ref> was named a Chevalier in the [[National Order of Quebec]] in 1992, and was named Woman of the Century by the Salon de la femme de Montréal in 1990.<ref name=ordre>{{cite web|url=http://www.ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca/membres/membre.asp?id=180 |title=Janette Bertrand |work=Ordre national du Québec |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518090148/http://www.ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca/membres/membre.asp?id=180 |archivedate=2015-05-18 |df= }}</ref>
Bertrand wrote the lyrics for the [[Celine Dion]] song "Berceuse", which was included on the ''[[D'Elles]]'' album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cdfrdp.qc.ca/centre/2009/07/jeanette-bertrand.html |title=Jeanette Bertrand : un modèle pour les femmes du Québec |date=July 3, 2009 |publisher=Centre des femmes de Rivière-des-Prairies}}</ref>
In 2003, she received the [[Prix Condorcet]], which is awarded annually to a public figure who has contributed to [[secularity]] and [[freedom of conscience]] in Quebec.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ledevoir.com/societe/ethique-et-religion/41858/en-bref-janette-bertrand-recoit-le-prix-condorcet |title=Janette Bertrand reçoit le Prix Condorcet |date=December 1, 2003 |newspaper=[[Le Devoir]]}}</ref>
Bertrand supported the [[Parti Québécois]]' proposed [[Quebec Charter of Values|Charter of Values]], arguing that accommodating religious minorities could lead to the erosion of women's rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/pq-makes-waves-with-values-charter-as-quebec-campaign-enters-home-stretch-1.2592187 |title=PQ makes waves with values charter as Quebec campaign enters home stretch |date=March 30, 2014 |publisher=CBC News - Montreal}}</ref>
